<section class="section getting-started-section">
  <div class="section-heading">
    <p class="eyebrow">Quickstart</p>
    <h1>Up and running in minutes</h1>
    <p class="lead">Install the <code>vexascript</code> npm package, write your first <code>.vx</code> file, add the VS Code extension for a full editor experience, and optionally embed a live Monaco editor in your own site.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="grid getting-started-grid">

    <article class="card getting-started-card">
      <div class="step-heading">
        <span class="step-badge">1</span>
        <h3>Install the CLI</h3>
      </div>
      <p>Install the <code>vexascript</code> package globally. The <code>vexa</code> binary becomes available immediately.</p>
{% highlightVexaScript %}
npm install -g vexascript
vexa --version
{% endhighlightVexaScript %}
      <p>Alternatively, run it without installing via <code>npx</code>:</p>
{% highlightVexaScript %}
npx vexascript run hello.vx
{% endhighlightVexaScript %}
    </article>

    <article class="card getting-started-card">
      <div class="step-heading">
        <span class="step-badge">2</span>
        <h3>Write your first file</h3>
      </div>
      <p>Create a <code>hello.vx</code> file. VexaScript is a TypeScript superset — valid TypeScript is valid VexaScript.</p>
{% highlightVexaScript %}
class Greeter(val name: string) {
  fun greet() => `Hello, ${name}!`
}

val g = Greeter("world")
console.log(g.greet())
{% endhighlightVexaScript %}
      <p>Run it directly or compile to JavaScript:</p>
{% highlightVexaScript %}
vexa run hello.vx
vexa build hello.vx -o dist/hello.js
{% endhighlightVexaScript %}
    </article>

    <article class="card getting-started-card">
      <div class="step-heading">
        <span class="step-badge">3</span>
        <h3>Install the VS Code extension</h3>
      </div>
      <p>The official extension gives you diagnostics, quick fixes, go-to-definition, hover docs, and completions as you type.</p>
      <div class="actions">
        <a class="button primary" href="https://marketplace.visualstudio.com/items?itemName=soywiz.vexascript-vscodeext" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Install VS Code extension</a>
      </div>
      <p>Once installed, open any <code>.vx</code> file and the language server starts automatically. Use the <a href="/syntax">syntax reference</a> or the <a href="/cli">CLI guide</a> to explore further.</p>
    </article>

    <article class="card getting-started-card">
      <div class="step-heading">
        <span class="step-badge">4</span>
        <h3>Run tests</h3>
      </div>
      <p>Test files use the <code>.test.vx</code> suffix. The <code>test</code> and <code>assert</code> helpers are available without any import.</p>
{% highlightVexaScript %}
test("arithmetic", () => {
  assert(1 + 1 == 2)
  assert(2 * 3 == 6)
})
{% endhighlightVexaScript %}
      <p>Run all tests under the current directory, or pass specific paths:</p>
{% highlightVexaScript %}
vexa test
vexa test src/math.test.vx
{% endhighlightVexaScript %}
    </article>

    <article class="card getting-started-card">
      <div class="step-heading">
        <span class="step-badge">5</span>
        <h3>Embed Monaco in your site</h3>
      </div>
      <p>The website bundle ships embeddable Monaco-powered editors. Drop a live, editable VexaScript snippet into any docs page or product demo.</p>
      <div class="actions">
        <a class="button secondary" href="/embed">Open the embed guide</a>
        <a class="button secondary" href="/playground">Try the playground</a>
      </div>
    </article>

    <article class="card getting-started-card">
      <div class="step-heading">
        <span class="step-badge">6</span>
        <h3>Read the docs</h3>
      </div>
      <p>Explore the full language, all CLI commands, and the embedding API.</p>
      <div class="actions">
        <a class="button secondary" href="/syntax">Syntax reference</a>
        <a class="button secondary" href="/cli">CLI guide</a>
        <a class="button secondary" href="/samples">Code samples</a>
      </div>
    </article>

  </div>
</section>
